column1: 5400446,AI,2023-09-28T12:01:27Z,high,Nice stream with good flow and abundant gravel throughout low gradients.  Adjacent property is northern wildlife design.  Crossing is currently 100% backwaters and passable to all life stages and species at these lower flow levels.                    ,"Culvert is in good shape, with some slight bending on the inlet and outlet

,Culvert does seem a bit under size for the crossing, with smaller amounts of fill.  However, the adjacent areas upstream and downstream are not much higher elevation than the stream channel so flows would likely be dissipated over the floodplain.          ","Stream is known fish bearing to the gradients to the Endako river.  Low amounts of fill makes construction easier,  however,  still expensive due to location on Highway 16.          ",2076441,,,,,,,5400446,,newgraph_airvine,newgraph_airvine,331,Rentoul Creek,Highway 16,,MOTI,Closed Bottom Structure,Round Culvert,,2.25,22,,2023-09-28,10,307446,6030655,No,,No,Yes,100,1,0,0.3,No,1.5,3.8,2,No,No,Deep Fill,High,,,10,,,,,,,,,newgraph_airvine,1,1,1,3,1,3,3,6,10,5,3,3,10,5,36,42,20230928_122420.jpg,20230928_122427.jpg,20230928_122441.jpg,20230928_122431.jpg,20230928_122422.jpg,20230928_122436.jpg,20230928_122447.jpg,,,20230928_122511.jpg,,,,,"<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC ""-//W3C//DTD HTML 4.0//EN"" ""http://www.w3.org/TR/REC-html40/strict.dtd"">

column1: 5400442,AI,2023-09-28T12:57:11Z,low," This is two 1.55 m pipes plus a 0.6 m overflow.  North large pipe has strange apron on inlet.  Stream is deeply insized (2.5 m deep) within agricultural field on downstream side.  No riparian for approximately 70 m downstream on right bank.  Stream is partially dewatered with stagnant pools throughout.  Forgie Creek dam,  owned by Hart George F/V B,  is upstream and may be influencing flow.  Channel is choked downstream with grasses in many places indicating flow is not occurring year around.           ",Major incision of channel downstream of the crossing indicates the stream could have a lot of volume at some times of year.  There is some evidence of erosion on the road prism on the downhill side with riprap placed around pipes.          , Channel appears very large downstream so culverts may be under sized.  Major highway.    ,"Multiple fish species noted upstream and downstream.  There are adjacent back roads,  but this is the main highway,  so construction would be difficult and expensive.          ",2883939,2076427,2076426,,,,,5400442,,newgraph_airvine,newgraph_airvine,332,Tributary to Endako River,Highway 16,,MOTI,Closed Bottom Structure,Round Culvert,,7.1,24,,2023-09-28,10,311759,6025526,No,,No,No,,1.8,0.85,1.3,No,2.5,10,1.5,No,No,Deep Fill,Medium,,,10,,,,,,,,,newgraph_airvine,4,2,1,7,3,3,9,16,10,5,2,3,10,5,35,51,20230928_132446.jpg,20230928_132459.jpg,20230928_132521.jpg,20230928_132753.jpg,20230928_132456.jpg,20230928_132515.jpg,20230928_132532.jpg,20230928_132540.jpg,,20230928_132657.jpg,,,,,"<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC ""-//W3C//DTD HTML 4.0//EN"" ""http://www.w3.org/TR/REC-html40/strict.dtd"">

column1: 5400216,AI,2023-09-29T10:56:54Z,low,Dry at time of survey.  Abundant gravels throughout.  Crossing on railway downstream still unassessed.  Modelled crossing below.  First 5 m of pipe is rusted through on the bottom side.  Deeply incised banks upstream indicate the stream has a lot of flow at sometimes in the year with a decent amount of power. 9m falls ~1km upstream.Upstream Co-op Lake stocked with KO from 2017-2023 and EB from 1963-2023.,"No blockage,  but there is significant erosion along the banks upstream for approximately 30 or 40 m.  This indicates the stream has a lot of power at some times of the year, although it was dry at the time of assessment.  The pipe is rusted all the way through the bottom for the 5 m downstream of the inlet.                  ","Because of the erosion upstream and because there is a road on the upstream and the downstream side perpendicular to the highway,  seems as though the stream would have higher than average risk of flood and over topping the road.  It’s a large watershed upstream as well.          ",Known fish bearing due to proximity to Endako River.  Major highway so all work is complicated and expensive. column1: 5400121,AI,2023-09-29T12:11:02Z,high,Small stream with very good flow immediately adjacent to the mainstem of the Endako River.  Could be valuable Chinook rearing area during high flow periods.  Pipe is bent in the middle so top half is backwatered but the bottom half is not.  Small outlet drop.  There is a large lump in the road at the pipe and pylons have been set up here likely to warn drivers.,Pipe is in extremely bad shape with large bend in the middle down and to the right.  Road has large lump on it with pylons set up likely to warn drivers.          ,"Because the pipe is very undersized and because flow is good even at this dry time of year, seems likely that this could be easily affected by a flood.          ",Very small road with no traffic and recreational access to Richmond Lake.  Fish presence assumed due to gradients and proximity to the Endako River. column1: 15600048,AI,2023-09-29T16:01:11Z,high,Two pipes (1.2m and 0.6m). 100% backwater. Guessing the pipes are embedded but cannot see due to poor water quality. This stream is extremely impacted by poor cattle ranching practices. There is no riparian fencing and cattle have completely trampled all the banks.  There is no riparian vegetation and water quality is extremely poor. This stream could likely be very productive for chinook and other species if eventually restored.           , Smaller of the two pipes is extremely old and rusted all the way through at the outlet.," Culverts are well undersized for the size of stream.  Rural setting,  agricultural fields adjacent so implications of flood seem fairly low.
,Assuming fish bearing due to proximity to the Nechako river and gradients.  Rural setting with small gravel road would make construction fairly straightforward and low cost.

column1: 15600277,AI,2023-09-30T13:43:26Z,high,"Very nice stream with excellent flow for this time of year on a dry year.  Very large deep outlet pool with extensive erosion undercutting the main pipe and 0.6 m overflow. Locally known as Dog Creek. Chinook captured upstream and downstream of Dog Creek FSR in 2021, 2022, and 2023 reported here https://a100.gov.bc.ca/pub/acat/public/viewReport.do?reportId=62942.  Connected to the Nechako River with observed chinook points downstream adjacent to the confluence. Road edge is failing at the culvert and eroding into stream. Highly degraded site upstream that would be a good candidate for restoration.      ",Both the main pipe and the overflow are undercut with erosion on the downstream side. Road edge will likely be failing and peeling back continuously.,Pipes are very under sized for the size of stream with evidence of significant erosion already present. Washout would have negative consequences for environmental values downstream.          ,Back road could likely be closed with access from either side. Low amounts of fill and small unpaved road width should make construction fairly simple.          ,1794340,,,booth2022SummaryMinnow,booth2023SummaryMinnow,booth2024SummaryMinnow,,15600277,,newgraph_airvine,newgraph_airvine,352,Tributary to Nechako River ,Dog Creek Road,,MOTI,Closed Bottom Structure,Round Culvert,,0.95,11.5,,2023-09-30,10,398933,5996365,No,,No,No,,1.5,0.4,1,No,3,2.7,3,Yes,Yes,Deep Fill,High,,,10,,,,,,,,,newgraph_airvine,4,3,1,8,5,3,15,23,2,1,9,7,10,9,38,61,20230930_140110.jpg,20230930_140157.jpg,20230930_140210.jpg,20230930_140201.jpg,20230930_140150.jpg,20230930_140205.jpg,,,,20230930_140307.jpg,20230930_140217.jpg,20230930_140233.jpg,Erosion downstream,Pool upstream ,"<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC ""-//W3C//DTD HTML 4.0//EN"" ""http://www.w3.org/TR/REC-html40/strict.dtd"">

column1: 15604478,AI,2023-09-30T14:17:41Z,high,"Extreme negative impacts due to cattle, particularly upstream of the FSR. Riparian exclusion fencing is required along with repairing vegetation, restoration irrigation, and monitoring. This is a fish bearing stream with high habitat values less than 2 km down the stream where it crosses Dog Creek Road.",Inlet partially blocked with debris. Some erosion present at the outlet.          ,"Because the upstream riparian has been completely destroyed by cattle, the stream has low resilience to high flow and flood events.          ","Low amounts of fill and low volume for an FSR with narrow width,  it would make replacement quite straightforward. column1: 15600285,MW,2023-09-11T17:26:25Z,high,"Two pipes (one at 1.8m, one at 1.5m), both with similar outlet drops. Inlet side has extensive beaver activity. Beaver dams are covering the inlet and culverts are not visible. Huge wetland upstream. Very big outlet pool so depth was estimated. Chinook were captured downstream of Settlement Road culvert in 2021 (https://a100.gov.bc.ca/pub/acat/public/viewReport.do?reportId=61991) and Rainbow Trout observed in stream from 2021-2023 (https://a100.gov.bc.ca/pub/acat/public/viewReport.do?reportId=61202 and https://a100.gov.bc.ca/pub/acat/public/viewReport.do?reportId=62942). Culverts should be replaced and beaver activity managed. Habitat looks good downstream. High habitat value at crossing upstream. ",Some erosion on outlet side.  Inlet side is severely blocked by beaver dams.,Large wetland area upstream of crossing next to road.  Flood could easily washout the road.,"Chinook were captured downstream of Settlement Road culvert in 2021 (https://a100.gov.bc.ca/pub/acat/public/viewReport.do?reportId=61991) and Rainbow Trout observed in stream from 2021-2023 (https://a100.gov.bc.ca/pub/acat/public/viewReport.do?reportId=61202 and https://a100.gov.bc.ca/pub/acat/public/viewReport.do?reportId=62942). column1: 15600112,MW,2023-09-12T08:23:29Z,low,"Stream not flowing at the time of assessment.  Horse pasture downstream.  Fenced off on both sides of pipe.  Nechako Environment and Water Stewardship Society ( https://newssociety.org/watersheds/goldie-creek ) report that stream was historically impacted adjacent to this site when Highway 27 was constructed 20-30 years ago due to fill from the excavation of the highway contributing significant amounts of sediment into Stoney Creek and ultimately into the spawning beds of Nechako White Sturgeon just below the Stoney Creek/Nechako River confluence. Extensive works completed upstream of the crossing in 2021 including culvert replaced with bridge, installation of beaver dam analogues, riparian planting and addition of large woody debris just upstream of the crossing. ",No issues at this time.,,"High fill depth, moderate traffic makes it a difficult fix. Stream could be flowing in the spring.",1806217,,,newssGoldieCreek,,,,15600112,,MateoW,MateoW,,Goldie Creek,Highway 27 S,,MOTI,Closed Bottom Structure,Round Culvert,,2.2,30,,2023-09-12,10,426644,5985671,No,,No,Yes,100,4,0,0.5,No,1,2.2,1.5,No,No,Deep Fill,Medium,,,10,,,,,,,,,MateoW,1,1,1,3,1,1,1,4,7,5,3,4,0,5,24,28,ignore_mobile/photos/TimePhoto_20230912_081637.jpg,ignore_mobile/photos/TimePhoto_20230912_082356.jpg,ignore_mobile/photos/TimePhoto_20230912_081742.jpg,ignore_mobile/photos/TimePhoto_20230912_082416.jpg,ignore_mobile/photos/TimePhoto_20230912_082009.jpg,ignore_mobile/photos/TimePhoto_20230912_081757.jpg,,,,ignore_mobile/photos/20230912_083221.jpg,,,,,"<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC ""-//W3C//DTD HTML 4.0//EN"" ""http://www.w3.org/TR/REC-html40/strict.dtd"">
